## **‚úÖ Benefits of This Organization**

| Benefit | Description |
|---------|-------------|
| **Clear Hierarchy** | Each UI system has its own panel |
| **Single Responsibility** | UIManager controls visibility, panels control content |
| **Easy to Find** | All Lantern UI elements under LanternUI panel |
| **No Conflicts** | Only one mini-game UI active at a time |
| **Scalable** | Easy to add new UI (GameEndUI, ShopUI, etc.) |
| **Testable** | Can test individual panels in isolation |
| **Clean Scene** | Canvas hierarchy mirrors code structure |

---

## **üéØ Recommended Approach for Your Project**

**Use the first approach (UIManager with explicit methods)** because:

1. ‚úÖ **Clear intent** - `ShowLanternGame()` is obvious
2. ‚úÖ **Easy debugging** - Can set breakpoints on specific show methods
3. ‚úÖ **Flexible** - Each panel can have custom show/hide logic
4. ‚úÖ **Simple** - No enum to maintain as you add UI
5. ‚úÖ **Unity-friendly** - Easy to wire up in Inspector

**Avoid:** Putting all UI elements in one giant panel - becomes unmaintainable fast!

---

## **üöÄ Setup Steps**

1. **Create Canvas** with these child panels
2. **Assign each panel its script** (LanternUI.cs, etc.)
3. **Create UIManager GameObject** with UIManager.cs
4. **Assign all panel references** in UIManager Inspector
5. **Set all panels inactive** except PersistentUI
6. **Test:** Call `UIManager.Instance.ShowLanternGame()` via ContextMenu

